    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="131"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d131">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/5637</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Norwegian Minister</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_BHH1"
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bryn</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 10, 1917</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring further to your note of November
                        13,<note n="1" xml:id="d131fn1">Not printed.</note> inquiring whether, under
                    the “Trading with the Enemy Act,” Norwegian business concerns whose commercial
                    intercourse with Germany is limited to the importation of goods from that
                    country, would by reason of that fact be excluded from commerce with the United
                    States, I have the honor to inform you that the War Trade Board to whom your
                    note under acknowledgment was referred for consideration, states that even
                    though the business of the Norwegian concerns be of the nature indicated, they
                    would be regarded as subject to the liabilities provided for in the act in
                    question. Any American firm dealing with a Norwegian concern engaged in business
                    of this character could do so only under license. The granting or withholding of
                    such a license by the War Trade Board would be dependent entirely upon the
                    circumstances of the particular case.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_PFL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Frank L. Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
